<h2>River Description</h2>
There are several ways to shorten this section to the length of your choice. The first section form
Esperance to Burtonsville begins with a section of flat water but culminates with the biggest water
entering Burtonsville.<br>
<br>
From Burtonsville to Mill Point there is a lot of class II and some class III. Especially as water
levels reach 3.0Ã¢ÂÂ on the Burtonsville gage. This is an enjoyable section with beautiful
scenery and several sections of rapids. There are the remains of a dam blow Lost Valley that
provides a wave to surf. Stay river right of the island and there are often waves in the narrow
channel. A quarter mile farther, under the 300 foot cliffs there are three small ledges the river
drops over. DonÃ¢ÂÂt miss noticing the falls coming off the cliff to your left.<br>
<br>
I have not paddled from Mill Point to Fort Hunter. The drop-per-mile is about half what it is up
stream.<br>
<br>
CFS changes dramatically on the Schoharie Creek, at 2 feet the gage shows 1580 cfs, at three feet
4430, and at 8 feet 36,300. The Creek runs 40,000 cfs or over during Spring runoff or a rainy
autumn week. Since the work has been taking place on the Schoharie Reservoir and the tube is
sending water into the Esopus the Schoharie Creek is over 2 feet less often.<br>
<br>
Esperance is located where US 20 crosses Schoharie Creek. Fort Hunter is located on river right at
the confluence of Schoharie Creek and the Mohawk River <br>
<div style='clear:both'>
